<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-773-536  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 773 536.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Lan Times  Sept 1989 v6 n9 p142(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Panacea for stressed-out invertebrates: backbones localize networktraffic, boosting overall network performance. (includes relatedarticles on physical ties and fiber optic technology)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Doering, David B.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Backbones tie together local area networks (LAN), distributingrather than centralizing network resources and management.andO;Departments can thus keep their own information on a LAN, but haveit available for other departments via the backbone.andP;  Choosing aprotocol and cabling scheme for the backbone is critical.andO;Ethernet provides a transmission rate of 10M-bps using a bustechnology and has one of the most widely installed bases.andO;Because of its reliance on collision architecture it may not beable to sustain high traffic loads.andP;  Token-ring protocol runs overshielded twisted-pair and provides a data rate of about 4M-bps.andP;  Aworkstation is able to transmit data when it has a special dataframe, the token.andP;  Token-bus protocol uses a logical rather thanphysical ring to move the token from one workstation to another.andO;Fiber optic cable has a strategic advantage over coaxial cablealthough it is more expensive.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Backbone NetworksWide Area NetworksConnectivityEthernetToken Ring NetworksCablesNetwork Management.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   A backbone divides the internetwork into discrete segments....andO;(chart)On a backbone the fastest node on an internetwork is only two'hops' away. (chart)A backbone reduces the number of 'hops' from LAN A to LAN E.andO;(chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>